        <!-- Section 1: The Newsbeat Identity -->
        <section id="introduction" class="mb-12 bg-white p-6 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 text-slate-800">Newsbeat's Dual Identity</h2>
            <p class="mb-4 text-slate-700">The AQA specification highlights Newsbeat as a key example of a 'transitional media product'. This reflects a fundamental shift in the media landscape. Newsbeat operates in two distinct modes: as a traditional, scheduled radio programme and as a dynamic, on-demand digital product. This dual nature presents both unique opportunities for audience engagement and significant challenges for the BBC as a Public Service Broadcaster (PSB) trying to connect with a competitive youth audience.</p>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-900">ðŸ“» Traditional Broadcast</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600">Scheduled broadcast times on BBC Radio 1, 1Xtra, and Asian Network. Follows a linear, pre-packaged format familiar to radio listeners.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-900">ðŸ“± Digital Platform</h3>
                    <p class="text-slate-600">Content is available online after broadcast. Utilises social media and other digital platforms for on-demand access and audience interaction, breaking the linear format.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: Interactive Theory Explorer -->
        <section id="theories" class="mb-12">
