                        why: "This theory is critically important for understanding the challenges Newsbeat faces in engaging its target audience. Even with the best intentions, the 'encoded' message of Newsbeat may not always be 'decoded' as intended by a diverse and media-literate youth audience, leading to declining engagement, as mentioned in the report.",
                        glossary: [
                            {term: "Encoding", definition: "The process by which media producers embed intended meanings into a media text."},
                            {term: "Decoding", definition: "The process by which audiences interpret and make sense of a media text's meaning."},
                            {term: "Preferred Reading (Dominant/Hegemonic)", definition: "The interpretation of a media text that aligns with the meaning intended by the producer and typically reinforces dominant societal ideologies."},
                            {term: "Negotiated Reading", definition: "An interpretation where the audience largely accepts the dominant meaning but adapts it to fit their own experiences and perspectives, often disagreeing with some aspects."},
                            {term: "Oppositional Reading", definition: "An interpretation where the audience actively rejects the dominant meaning of a media text and understands it in a contrary or critical way."},
                            {term: "Ideology", definition: "A system of beliefs and values that shapes a society or group's understanding of the world."}
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        theorist: "Henry Jenkins: Fandoms / Participatory Culture",
                        idea: "Henry Jenkins argues that the rise of digital media has fostered a 'participatory culture' where audiences are no longer just passive consumers but active participants. They can engage with media producers, create their own content (fan fiction, memes), and often form 'fandoms' around specific media texts or personalities, particularly through social media.",
                        application: "Newsbeat actively tries to harness this 'participatory culture' through its multi-platform strategy. It uses social media (like Twitter) to create immediacy, offer behind-the-scenes glimpses, run Q&As with journalists, and solicit direct feedback or user-generated content. This strategy aims to build a sense of community and foster direct engagement beyond the traditional broadcast.",
                        why: "Jenkins' theory directly explains Newsbeat's digital-first approach. It's not enough to just broadcast; Newsbeat must actively encourage interaction and participation to build a loyal, engaged audience in a world where audiences expect to be heard and to contribute, moving from a one-way broadcast to a two-way conversation.",
                        glossary: [
                            {term: "Participatory Culture", definition: "A culture in which fans and other consumers are invited to actively participate in the creation and circulation of new content."},
                            {term: "Fandoms", definition: "Communities of fans who share a common interest in a particular media text, celebrity, or genre, often engaging in creative and social activities related to their interest."},
                            {term: "Passive Consumers", definition: "Audiences who receive media messages without actively engaging with or responding to them."},
                            {term: "User-Generated Content (UGC)", definition: "Content created and published by users of a platform rather than by traditional media producers (e.g., social media posts, fan art)."},
                            {term: "Transmedia Storytelling", definition: "A process where integral elements of a fiction are dispersed systematically across multiple delivery channels for the purpose of creating a unified and coordinated entertainment experience."}
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        theorist: "David Gauntlett: Identity Theory",
                        idea: "David Gauntlett argues that media today provides a diverse range of 'identities' and role models that audiences can 'pick and mix' from to construct their own sense of self. He suggests that media offers tools and resources for identity formation in a fluid, post-modern world, moving away from older ideas of media imposing identities.",
                        application: "Newsbeat strives to offer content that represents diverse class, racial, gender, and age (15-29) identities within its target demographic. By featuring a variety of perspectives and stories, Newsbeat can provide young people with different 'tools' for understanding themselves and others, fulfilling its 'educate' and 'inform' remit by reflecting and challenging societal norms and offering diverse role models.",
                        why: "This theory shows how Newsbeat contributes to the social good beyond just delivering news. By representing diverse identities and experiences, it can help young people explore and understand their own place in the world, reinforcing or challenging their views, which is a key part of personal development and aligns with the BBC's PSB values.",
                        glossary: [
                            {term: "Identity Formation", definition: "The process by which individuals develop a sense of who they are, often influenced by social, cultural, and media factors."},
                            {term: "'Pick and Mix' Identities", definition: "The idea that individuals can selectively choose and combine different aspects or representations of identity from media and culture to construct their own unique sense of self."},
                            {term: "Role Models", definition: "Individuals whose behaviour, example, or success is or can be emulated by others."},
                            {term: "Post-Modern World", definition: "A contemporary societal condition characterized by diversity, fragmentation, and skepticism towards grand narratives, where individuals have more freedom to define themselves."}
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        theorist: "Gerbner: Cultivation Theory",
                        idea: "George Gerbner's Cultivation Theory suggests that prolonged and heavy exposure to media (especially television) gradually 'cultivates' or shapes a viewer's perception of reality to align with the worldview presented in the media. It focuses on the cumulative effect of media messages rather than immediate behavioural changes.",
                        application: "For Newsbeat, if young audiences are consistently exposed to particular representations of news, society, or certain social issues through its various platforms, this consistent exposure could, over time, cultivate their understanding and perception of these realities. For example, if Newsbeat frequently covers stories about youth activism, it might cultivate a view among its audience that young people are active agents of social change.",
                        why: "Cultivation theory is useful for examining the long-term, subtle effects of Newsbeat's consistent messaging on its youth audience's worldview. It helps media students consider how the BBC's editorial choices and content selection might cumulatively shape the perceptions of young people about their society, current events, and their role within it, even if these effects are not immediately obvious.",
                        glossary: [
                            {term: "Cultivation", definition: "The process by which long-term exposure to media content gradually shapes a viewer's perceptions of social reality."},
                            {term: "Mainstreaming", definition: "The process by which heavy viewers from different social groups develop a common outlook on the world through constant exposure to the same media messages."},
                            {term: "Resonance", definition: "When a viewer's lived reality strongly matches the reality portrayed in media, leading to a stronger cultivation effect."},
                            {term: "Mean World Syndrome", definition: "A perception by heavy television viewers that the world is more dangerous than it actually is, often a result of constant exposure to violence in media."}
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        theorist: "Uses & Gratifications",
                        idea: "The Uses and Gratifications theory (an audience-centred approach) suggests that audiences are active, not passive, and consciously choose media to satisfy specific needs. These needs are typically categorised as: 1) Information/Surveillance, 2) Personal Identity/Self-discovery, 3) Social Interaction/Integration, and 4) Entertainment/Diversion.",
                        application: "Newsbeat explicitly aims to satisfy all four of these needs for its youth audience. It provides news and current affairs (Information), covers issues relevant to young people (Personal Identity), offers topics for discussion with peers (Social Interaction), and presents content in an engaging, accessible format (Entertainment).",
                        why: "This foundational theory explains the 'why' behind audience consumption. The success of Newsbeat in a highly competitive media landscape critically depends on how effectively and consistently it can satisfy these diverse gratifications for its target demographic compared to the myriad of other digital content providers available to young people.",
                        glossary: [
                            {term: "Active Audience", definition: "The concept that audiences are not passive recipients of media messages but actively interpret and engage with media based on their own needs and contexts."},
                            {term: "Information/Surveillance", definition: "The need to stay informed about current events, society, and the world."},
                            {term: "Personal Identity/Self-discovery", definition: "The need to reinforce personal values, gain insights into oneself, or find role models through media."},
                            {term: "Social Interaction/Integration", definition: "The need to connect with others, find common ground, or enhance social interactions through media content."},
                            {term: "Entertainment/Diversion", definition: "The need for escape, relaxation, or emotional arousal provided by media."},
                            {term: "Gratifications", definition: "The satisfactions or benefits that audiences derive from consuming media."}
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            };

            const container = document.getElementById('theory-cards-container');
            const industryBtn = document.getElementById('industry-btn');
            const audienceBtn = document.getElementById('audience-btn');

            // Function to set the active/inactive state of buttons
            function setActiveButton(buttonToActivate, buttonToDeactivate) {
                buttonToActivate.classList.remove('btn-inactive');
                buttonToActivate.classList.add('btn-active');
                buttonToDeactivate.classList.remove('btn-active');
                buttonToDeactivate.classList.add('btn-inactive');
            }

            function createCard(theory) {
                let glossaryHtml = '';
                if (theory.glossary && theory.glossary.length > 0) {
                    glossaryHtml = `
                        <div class="mt-4 pt-4 border-t border-slate-200">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-md text-slate-700 mb-2">Key Terms:</h4>
                            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-slate-600 space-y-1">
                                ${theory.glossary.map(item => `
                                    <li><strong>${item.term}:</strong> ${item.definition}</li>
                                `).join('')}
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    `;
                }

                return `
                    <div class="theory-card bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-slate-200" data-theorist="${theory.theorist}">
                        <div class="p-4 flex justify-between items-center">
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg text-slate-800">${theory.theorist}</h3>
                             <div class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center bg-slate-200 rounded-full">
                                <span class="icon-plus text-slate-600 font-bold text-lg">+</span>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="details px-4 pb-4">
                            <div class="border-t border-slate-200 pt-4">
                                <p class="mb-3"><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-700">Core Idea:</strong> <span class="text-slate-600">${theory.idea}</span></p>
                                <p class="mb-3"><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-700">Application to Newsbeat:</strong> <span class="text-slate-600">${theory.application}</span></p>
                                <p><strong class="font-semibold text-slate-700">Why it's useful:</strong> <span class="text-slate-600">${theory.why}</span></p>
                                ${glossaryHtml}
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                `;
            }

            function renderCards(type) {
                container.innerHTML = theories[type].map(createCard).join('');
                addCardListeners();
            }
            
            industryBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
                // Only act if not already the active button
                if (!industryBtn.classList.contains('btn-active')) {
                    renderCards('industry');
                    setActiveButton(industryBtn, audienceBtn);
                }
            });

            audienceBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
                // Only act if not already the active button
                if (!audienceBtn.classList.contains('btn-active')) {
                    renderCards('audience');
                    setActiveButton(audienceBtn, industryBtn);
                }
            });
            
            function addCardListeners() {
                const cards = document.querySelectorAll('.theory-card');
                cards.forEach(card => {
                    card.addEventListener('click', () => {
                        // Close any other open cards
                        cards.forEach(otherCard => {
                            if (otherCard !== card && otherCard.classList.contains('active')) {
                                otherCard.classList.remove('active');
                            }
                        });
                        // Toggle the clicked card
                        card.classList.toggle('active');
                    });
                });
            }

            // Initial setup on page load
            setActiveButton(industryBtn, audienceBtn); // Set initial button active state
            renderCards('industry'); // Render industry theories initially

            // Chart.js implementation
            const ctx = document.getElementById('listenershipChart').getContext('2d');
            const listenershipChart = new Chart(ctx, {
                type: 'bar',
                data: {
                    labels: ['2018', '2020', '2022', '2024 (proj.)'],
                    datasets: [{
                        label: 'Weekly Youth Listeners (Illustrative)',
                        data: [5.1, 4.5, 3.9, 3.4], // Example data
                        backgroundColor: 'rgba(71, 85, 105, 0.6)', // slate-600
                        borderColor: 'rgba(51, 65, 85, 1)', // slate-700
                        borderWidth: 1
                    }]
                },
                options: {
                    responsive: true,
                    maintainAspectRatio: false,
                    scales: {
                        y: {
                            beginAtZero: true,
                            title: {
                                display: true,
                                text: 'Listeners (in millions)'
                            }
                        }
                    },
                    plugins: {
                        legend: {
                            display: false
                        },
                        tooltip: {
                            callbacks: {
                                label: function(context) {
                                    return `${context.dataset.label}: ${context.parsed.y} million`;
                                }
                            }
                        }
                    }
                }
            });
        });
    </script>

</body>
</html>
